SIMPLE: retaliate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Retaliate
<hw>Re*tal"i*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Retaliated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Retaliating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>retaliatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>retaliare</ets> to retaliate; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + a word akin to <ets>talio</ets> talion,
retaliation. Cf. <er>Talion</er>.]</ety> <def>To return the like for; to
repay or requite by an act of the same kind; to return evil for (evil).
[Now seldom used except in a bad sense.]</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One ambassador sent word to the duke's son that his visit should
be <qex>retaliated</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is unlucky to be obliged to <qex>retaliate</qex> the injuries
of authors, whose works are so soon forgotten that we are in danger of
appearing the first aggressors.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retaliate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Retaliate
<hw>Re*tal"i*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To return like for like;
specifically, to return evil for evil; <as>as, to <ex>retaliate</ex>
upon an enemy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retaliation</ent>⟦br⟧
